# Collections + SQL Assessment Day: Integration Patterns and Practical Synthesis

## Connecting Java Collections to SQL Query Results
Every JPA and JDBC operation maps database results to Java collections. Understanding this mapping is critical for performance.

```java
// JPA — Spring Data returns List<T> for multi-row queries
List<Order> orders = orderRepository.findByStatus("PENDING");
// Internally: SELECT * FROM orders WHERE status='PENDING' → ResultSet → ArrayList<Order>

// SQL GROUP BY → Collectors.groupingBy in Java
// SQL: SELECT status, COUNT(*) FROM orders GROUP BY status
Map<String, Long> countsByStatus = orders.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(Order::getStatus, Collectors.counting()));

// SQL ORDER BY → Collections.sort or stream().sorted()
// SQL: SELECT * FROM orders ORDER BY total DESC
orders.sort(Comparator.comparing(Order::getTotal).reversed());

// SQL DISTINCT → Set or stream().distinct()
// SQL: SELECT DISTINCT customer_id FROM orders
Set<String> uniqueCustomers = orders.stream()
    .map(Order::getCustomerId)
    .collect(Collectors.toSet());

// SQL JOIN → stream flatMap or nested loops
// SQL: SELECT p.name, oi.quantity FROM products p JOIN order_items oi ON p.id = oi.product_id
List<ProductQuantity> result = orderItems.stream()
    .map(oi -> new ProductQuantity(productMap.get(oi.getProductId()), oi.getQuantity()))
    .collect(toList());
```

## N+1 Query Problem — The #1 JPA Performance Bug
```java
// BAD: N+1 queries — 1 query for all orders + 1 query per order for its items
List<Order> orders = orderRepository.findAll(); // 1 SQL query
for (Order order : orders) {
    order.getItems().size(); // triggers lazy load → 1 SQL per order!
}
// For 1000 orders: 1001 SQL queries

// GOOD: JOIN FETCH — 1 query for everything
List<Order> orders = orderRepository.findAllWithItems(); // in repository
// @Query("SELECT o FROM Order o JOIN FETCH o.items WHERE o.status = :status")
// Result: 1 SQL query with JOIN, Hibernate assembles the Order→items graph
```

## SQL Assessment Concepts — Core Queries
```sql
-- GROUP BY with HAVING (after-group filter)
SELECT customer_id, COUNT(*) as order_count, SUM(total) as revenue
FROM orders
WHERE status = 'COMPLETED'
GROUP BY customer_id
HAVING SUM(total) > 10000
ORDER BY revenue DESC;

-- Window functions (advanced)
SELECT order_id, total,
    SUM(total) OVER (PARTITION BY customer_id ORDER BY created_at) as running_total,
    RANK() OVER (ORDER BY total DESC) as rank
FROM orders;

-- Subquery
SELECT * FROM products
WHERE id IN (
    SELECT DISTINCT product_id FROM order_items
    WHERE quantity > 10
);

-- EXISTS (often faster than IN for large subqueries)
SELECT * FROM customers c
WHERE EXISTS (
    SELECT 1 FROM orders o WHERE o.customer_id = c.id AND o.status = 'PENDING'
);
```

## Collection Choice Summary Card
| Requirement | Use |
|---|---|
| Fast key-value lookup, no order | HashMap |
| Key-value in insertion order | LinkedHashMap |
| Key-value sorted by key | TreeMap |
| Unique elements, fast lookup | HashSet |
| Unique elements, insertion order | LinkedHashSet |
| Unique elements, sorted | TreeSet |
| Ordered list, fast random access | ArrayList |
| Ordered list, fast add/remove at ends | ArrayDeque |
| Sorted unique, range queries | TreeSet / TreeMap |
| Concurrent reads and writes | ConcurrentHashMap |
| Read-heavy, occasional write | CopyOnWriteArrayList |
| Fixed-size buffer, index access | Array |

## Full Pipeline Pattern — Repository → Service → Controller
```java
// Repository (data layer)
public interface OrderRepository extends JpaRepository<Order, String> {
    @Query("SELECT o FROM Order o JOIN FETCH o.items WHERE o.customerId = :cid")
    List<Order> findByCustomerIdWithItems(@Param("cid") String customerId);
}

// Service (business logic layer) — entities → DTOs, business rules
@Service
public class OrderService {
    public Map<String, List<OrderDto>> getOrdersByStatus(String customerId) {
        List<Order> orders = repo.findByCustomerIdWithItems(customerId);
        return orders.stream()
            .map(this::toDto)
            .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(OrderDto::getStatus));
    }
    // Returns Map<status, List<OrderDto>> — never null, empty map if no orders
}

// Controller (HTTP layer) — DTOs in, DTOs out
@GetMapping("/customers/{id}/orders")
public ResponseEntity<Map<String, List<OrderDto>>> getOrders(@PathVariable String id) {
    Map<String, List<OrderDto>> result = orderService.getOrdersByStatus(id);
    return result.isEmpty() ? ResponseEntity.noContent().build() : ResponseEntity.ok(result);
}
```

## DSA: Collections in Algorithm Problems
```java
// Stack for bracket matching
public boolean isValid(String s) {
    Deque<Character> stack = new ArrayDeque<>();
    for (char c : s.toCharArray()) {
        if (c=='(' || c=='{' || c=='[') stack.push(c);
        else if (stack.isEmpty() || !matches(stack.pop(), c)) return false;
    }
    return stack.isEmpty();
}

// HashMap for frequency count (Top K elements)
public List<Integer> topKFrequent(int[] nums, int k) {
    Map<Integer,Integer> freq = new HashMap<>();
    for (int n : nums) freq.merge(n, 1, Integer::sum);
    return freq.entrySet().stream()
        .sorted(Map.Entry.<Integer,Integer>comparingByValue().reversed())
        .limit(k)
        .map(Map.Entry::getKey)
        .collect(toList());
}

// Two-pointer with sorted data
public int[] twoSum(int[] nums, int target) { // sorted array version
    int l=0, r=nums.length-1;
    while (l<r) {
        int sum = nums[l]+nums[r];
        if (sum==target) return new int[]{l,r};
        else if (sum<target) l++;
        else r--;
    }
    return new int[]{};
}
```

## Common Assessment Topics
1. **HashMap vs TreeMap vs LinkedHashMap** — when to use each
2. **ArrayList vs LinkedList** — performance trade-offs
3. **ConcurrentHashMap** — why HashMap is not thread-safe
4. **equals/hashCode contract** — what breaks without it
5. **N+1 query problem** — identify and fix with JOIN FETCH
6. **SQL GROUP BY + HAVING vs WHERE** — filtering before/after aggregation
7. **Stream collectors** — groupingBy, counting, joining, toMap

